- yash-random-y-tst-hangs: `tests/yash/random-y.tst` hangs (bounded by
  CTest's 120s per-file TIMEOUT). The rest of the suite is fine.
  `$RANDOM` itself varies correctly when checked directly, so the
  two busy-`until`-loops at the top aren't the obvious cause; more
  likely the later cases piping a function's output through subshells
  (`print > seeded1; print > seeded2; diff seeded1 seeded2`), similar
  in shape to `subshell-exit-trap-output-misdirected`. Not isolated to
  a specific line yet.

- sh-onsig-async-unsafe: `sh_onsig()` (`src/sh/sh_main.c`'s SIGCHLD
  handler) calls `term_erase()`/`term_restore()`/`prompt_show()`/
  `buffer_*` directly from signal-handler context -- none of that is
  async-signal-safe. Latent race, not a deterministic failure.

    sleep 1 &
    sleep 2 &
    wait

  Proposed fix (2026-07-24, not implemented): shrink `sh_onsig()` to
  only `wait_nohang()`/`job_signal()` (both safe -- plain memory
  writes, no I/O), matching the pattern `job_signal()`/`job_update()`/
  `job_clean()` already use correctly for job-done banners. Extend
  `job_clean()` to also announce newly-*stopped* jobs the same way, so
  the stopped-job banner moves out of the handler too.

  The harder part: repainting the prompt while `term_read()` is
  blocked mid-line can't just defer to `job_update()` (that only runs
  between whole statements). An EINTR-based nudge won't work either --
  every signal here installs via `sig_action()` with `SA_RESTART`
  unconditionally set (no `FLAG_PREFERSELECT`), so the kernel silently
  restarts the interrupted `read()` before `term_read()` ever sees it.
  Recommended: the standard self-pipe trick (as bash/zsh/dash use) --
  `sh_onsig()` writes one byte to a pipe (async-signal-safe); `term_read()`
  blocks on `select()`/`poll()` over both the terminal fd and the
  pipe instead of a bare `read()`, doing the real repaint in ordinary
  context when the pipe wakes it. New dependency (`select`/`poll`,
  unused elsewhere in the tree) but both are plain POSIX syscalls.
